Recent years have seen some promising steps forward, yet the result is a morass of conflicting policies that leave women without a clear answer. More to the point, it gives women little choice over their own destinies.

Women must decide between risking prison time and potential domestic violence or seeking abortion illegally and putting their lives at risk.

OUTLAWING THE SAFE HAVEN: THE LEGAL IMPEDIMENTS IN COSTA RICA

Costa Rica outlaws any form of abortion. Any woman who terminates a pregnancy faces up to three years in prison. The Almost Never League, a Costa Rican group that pushes an anti-abortion agenda, has proposed the torture and death penalty for women who undergo abortions, but this idea has garnered little public support.

Restrictions on abortion in Costa Rica are the same regardless of the woman’s personal circumstances. Mothers whose children have abnormalities and young women who discover themselves pregnant with unwanted children receive the same penalty.

JUST A CHILD?

If she is under 18 years old, a woman can’t legally give consent for an abortion in Costa Rica. But there’s no way for court to verify the age of the victim, especially in a country where many young women are exploited by their partners.
